2 Normalitzaci√≥ de les variables qualitatives

Com hem comentat en l‚Äôapartat anterior, la interpretaci√≥ del tipus de les dades segons R √©s err√≤nia. En aquest apartat, realitzarem la transformaci√≥ corresponent de les variables qualitatives del nostre conjunt de dades. Aquestes variables s√≥n: athlete, female, white i black.

Pr√®viament, realitzarem una c√≤pia del dataset original, i sobre aquest segon aplicarem totes les transformacions de normalitzaci√≥.

## Duplicate df to do the cleaning tasks
df.clean <- df.raw

2.1 Athlete

El tipus de la variable athlete √©s character. A la vegada, podem veure que els valors √∫nics d‚Äôaquest atribut, s√≥n m√©s dels esperats. √âs per aquest motiu, que, en primer lloc, haurem de modificar aquests valors per tal de nom√©s tenir ‚ÄòTRUE‚Äô i ‚ÄòFALSE‚Äô, i finalment codificar les variables com a tipus ‚Äòfactor‚Äô.

typeof(df.clean$athlete)
## [1] "character"
unique(df.clean$athlete)
## [1] "TRUE"  "FALSE" "false" "true"
#Revalue to unique 
df.clean$athlete <- revalue (x = df.clean$athlete, c("true"="TRUE", "false"="FALSE"))
unique(df.clean$athlete)
## [1] "TRUE"  "FALSE"

Un cop disposem de valors √∫nics, realitzarem la transformaci√≥ cap a valors de tipus ‚Äòlogical‚Äô i per acabar, codificarem la variable categ√≤rica com a tipus ‚Äòfactor‚Äô tal com indica l‚Äôenunciat.

#Cast to Logical data type
castToLogical <- function(data){
  data <- as.logical(data)
}

df.clean$athlete <- castToLogical(df.clean$athlete)
#checking if its logical
typeof(df.clean$athlete)
## [1] "logical"
unique(df.clean$athlete)
## [1]  TRUE FALSE
#Cast to Factor vectors
factorVectorGeneration <- function(data){
  f <- factor(data)
}
df.clean$athlete <- factorVectorGeneration(df.clean$athlete)

#Checking Factor
typeof(df.clean$athlete)
## [1] "integer"
unique(df.clean$athlete)
## [1] TRUE  FALSE
## Levels: FALSE TRUE
levels(df.clean$athlete)
## [1] "FALSE" "TRUE"
nlevels(df.clean$athlete)
## [1] 2
sapply(df.clean,class)

3.2 Hores totals cursades al semestre

El tipus retornat de la variable ‚Äòtothrs‚Äô √©s ‚Äòcharacter‚Äô. Observant que es tracta d‚Äôuna variable quantitativa, hem de realitzar una conversi√≥ a tipus ‚Äònumeric‚Äô. Per dur a terme aquesta transformaci√≥ creem una funci√≥ que elimini la unitat de la variable, converteixi les comes en punts i faci un cast a tipus ‚Äònumeric‚Äô.

#Type checking
sapply(df.clean,class)
##         sat      tothrs       hsize      hsrank      hsperc      colgpa 
##   "integer" "character" "character"   "integer"   "numeric"   "numeric" 
##     athlete      female       white       black 
##    "factor"    "factor"    "factor"    "factor"
#There is no NA value
any(is.na(df.clean$sat))
## [1] FALSE
#Transform without units, comma -> dot and numeric datatype
cleanAndExtractNum <- function(row){
  num <- gsub("[a-zA-Z ]", "", row) #Elimiem caracters
  num <- as.numeric(gsub(",", ".",num)) #Comma to dot, to numeric
}
df.clean$tothrs <- cleanAndExtractNum(df.clean$tothrs)

#Checking type
sapply(df.clean,class)
##         sat      tothrs       hsize      hsrank      hsperc      colgpa 
##   "integer"   "numeric" "character"   "integer"   "numeric"   "numeric" 
##     athlete      female       white       black 
##    "factor"    "factor"    "factor"    "factor"
head(df.clean)
##    sat tothrs     hsize hsrank   hsperc colgpa athlete female white black

6 Creaci√≥ d‚Äôuna nova variable

#Import library
library('mappings')
#Setting intervals
gpaletter_intervals <- c(0,1.50, 2.50, 3.50, 4.01)
#Creating mapping function
m <- cut_mapping(gpaletter_intervals, right=FALSE, to=c("D", "C", "B", "A"))
#print function
print(m)

df.clean$gpaletter<- m(df.clean$colgpa)
